Path: godot/tutorials/animation/cutout_animation.rst
Summary: This section covers the initial setup of a skeletal rig for cutout animation in Godot, starting with the root node and adding the hip and torso sprites.

Create an empty Node2D as root of the scene.

The first node of the model is the hip. Generally, both in 2D and 3D, the hip is the root of the skeleton. This makes it easier to animate.

Next will be the torso. The torso needs to be a child of the hip. Create a child sprite and load the torso texture, then accommodate it properly.

To test the hierarchy, press E to enter rotate mode and drag with the left mouse button to rotate the torso. Press ESC to exit rotate mode.

The rotation pivot is wrong and needs to be adjusted. This small cross in the middle of the Sprite2D is the rotation pivot.
---CHUNK---
Document: Cutout Animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/cutout_animation.rst
Summary: This section explains how to adjust the pivot point of a Sprite2D and introduces a common problem with 2D node depth ordering, hinting at a solution using RemoteTransform2D.

The pivot of a Sprite2D can be adjusted by changing its *offset* property. Alternatively, you can visually adjust the pivot by hovering over the desired pivot point and pressing V. A toolbar tool also offers similar functionality.

When constructing a character, add body pieces sequentially, starting with the right arm. Ensure each sprite is placed correctly within the scene hierarchy so its transformations are relative to its parent.

A common issue arises with child nodes in 2D: they appear in front of their parents. For instance, if the left arm is a child of the hip, it will render in front of the hip and torso. While moving the left arm nodes above the hip in the hierarchy would visually place it behind, this breaks the intended hierarchical relationship, preventing it from being affected by the torso's movement. This depth ordering problem can be resolved using RemoteTransform2D nodes.

Note: Depth ordering issues can also be addressed by modifying the Z property of any Node2D-derived node.
---CHUNK---
Document: Cutout Animation Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/cutout_animation.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use the RemoteTransform2D node to control the position and animation of nodes in a cutout animation setup.
RemoteTransform2D node
The RemoteTransform2D node transforms nodes somewhere else in the hierarchy. This node applies its own transform (including any transformation it inherits from its parents) to the remote node it targets.

This allows us to correct the visibility order of our elements, independently of the locations of those parts in the cutout hierarchy.

Create a RemoteTransform2D node as a child of the torso. Call it remote_arm_l.
Create another RemoteTransform2D node inside the first and call it remote_hand_l.
Use the Remote Path property of the two new nodes to target the arm_l and hand_l sprites respectively.

Moving the RemoteTransform2D nodes now moves the sprites. So we can create animations by adjusting the RemoteTransform2D transforms.
---CHUNK---
Document: Cutout Animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/cutout_animation.rst
Summary: This section explains how to complete a cutout rig and discusses its limitations, setting the stage for introducing Godot's skeletons.

The resulting rig will be easy to animate. By selecting the nodes and rotating them you can animate forward kinematics (FK) efficiently.

For simple objects and rigs this is fine, but there are limitations:
- Selecting sprites in the main viewport can become difficult in complex rigs. The scene tree ends up being used to select parts instead, which can be slower.
- Inverse Kinematics (IK) is useful for animating extremities like hands and feet, and can't be used with our rig in its current state.

To solve these problems we'll use Godot's skeletons.
---CHUNK---
Document: Cutout Animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/cutout_animation.rst
Summary: This section explains how to create skeletons and bones in Godot for cutout animation, including how to add endpoint nodes and clear unwanted bones.
Skeletons
In Godot, a helper is available to create "bones" between nodes. The nodes linked by bones are called skeletons.

To create a skeleton, select a chain of nodes from top to bottom. Then, click on the Skeleton menu and select "Make Bones".

This action adds bones to the selected chain. A bone connects a node with its parent. If a node has no child, the bone generation might stop unexpectedly, leaving a gap.

To ensure proper bone orientation and connection, create an endpoint node. A Marker2D node is recommended as it is visible in the editor. This endpoint node will serve as the child for the last bone in the chain.

After creating the endpoint node, select the entire chain, from the endpoint to the starting node, and create bones using the Skeleton menu.

The resulting skeleton will more closely resemble a proper rigging, allowing for animation of articulated parts.

It is advisable to create endpoints for all important extremities and generate bones for all articultable parts of the cutout, with the hip serving as the primary connection point for all chains.

If an extra bone is created when connecting the hip and torso (connecting the hip node to the scene root), select the root and hip node, open the Skeleton menu, and click "Clear Bones" to remove it.

The final skeleton should have bones connecting all articulated parts. The presence of additional endpoint nodes in extremities will be relevant for subsequent steps like setting up IK chains.

IK chains are a feature that allows for more natural control of extremities.
---CHUNK---
Document: Cutout Animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/cutout_animation.rst
Summary: This section explains how to set up and use Inverse Kinematics (IK) chains in Godot for animating character extremities.
IK stands for inverse kinematics. It's a convenient technique for animating the position of hands, feet and other extremities of rigs. Without IK chains, each motion of the foot would require rotating and positioning several other bones (the shin and the thigh at least), which would be complex and imprecise. IK allows moving the foot directly while the shin and thigh self-adjust.
Note: IK chains in Godot currently work in the editor only, not at runtime. They are intended to ease the process of setting keyframes and are not currently useful for techniques like procedural animation.
To create an IK chain, select a chain of bones from endpoint to the base for the chain. For example, to create an IK chain for the right leg, select the following bones:
Then enable this chain for IK by going to Edit > Make IK Chain.
As a result, the base of the chain will turn yellow.
Once the IK chain is set up, grab any child or grandchild of the base of the chain (e.g., a foot) and move it. You'll see the rest of the chain adjust as you move its position.
---CHUNK---
